{
  "doc_id": "41316",
  "text": "[Adapted from Dempsey et al. [CITATION_1] .] [CITATION_2] . Furthermore, expiratory flow limitation and prolonged expiratory time during heavy exercise often result in positive intrathoracic pressures that meet or exceed those at which dynamic compression of the airways occurs [CITATION_3] . Positive intrathoracic pressures will reduce ventricular transmural pressure, thereby decreasing the rate of ventricular filling during diastole, and reducing stroke volume and cardiac output [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Active expiration against positive resistance impedes femoral venous return, even in the face of an active \"muscle pump\" [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . These extra expiratory effects may compromise systemic O 2 delivery (7) and render the working limb musculature even more susceptible to fatigue.",
